n which gender takes center stage. She shows how notions of female and male were developed by the rabbis of Roman Palestine and why the distinctions were so important in the formation of their religious and legal tradition.Rabbinic attention to women, men, sexuality, and gender took place within the "ordinary tedium of everyday life, in acts that were both familiar and mundane." While spinners and weavers performed what seemed like ordinary tasks, their craft was in fact symbolic of larger gender and sexual issues, which Peskowitz deftly explicates. Her study of ancient spinning and her abundant source material will set new standards in the fields of gender studies, Jewish studies, and cultural studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aRabbinical literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aSex in rabbinical literature. 0aSex rolexReligious aspectsxJudaism. 0aTextile crafts in rabbinical literature. 0aWomen in rabbinical literature. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh  achallenges traditional assumptions.  aclassic form of religion.  acritical moment in jewish history.  adestruction of jerusalem temple.  afeminist interpretation.  ajudaisms historical development.  anew incarnations of judaism.  arabbinic judaism.  arabbis of roman palestine.  astudy of ancient spinning.  aunderstanding of early rabbinic judaism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020967140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520919495?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520919495423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520919495/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY